{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516665"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12674"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12674"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.72,0.05,0.02,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111939"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5150"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94003"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45490"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111939"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents with a three-week history of coughing up blood. He reports at least five to six episodes every 2\u20133 days of coughing up bright red blood, approximately one to two tablespoons on each occasion. He also has mild shortness of breath, but no chest pain, fevers, chills, or recent travel. He has also noticed a generalised weakness and recently developed leg muscle cramps, making it difficult for him to rise from a chair. His medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and hypertension. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and still smokes one pack a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is alert and not in respiratory distress. His blood pressure is 132/80 mmHg, pulse 76/min, temperature 37.4\u00a0\u00b0C, respiratory rate 22/min and SpO2 94% on room air. Chest auscultation demonstrates a prolonged expiratory phase with end-expiratory wheezing. There are reduced breath sounds in the right upper chest. Neurological examination demonstrates 3/5 hip flexion power and decreased deep tendon reflexes bilaterally. Standard haematological and biochemical laboratory tests are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thymoma","Lung cancer","Tuberculosis","Pneumonia","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s age, smoking history, and symptoms of coughing up blood (haemoptysis) are highly concerning for lung cancer. The mass lesion seen on the chest X-ray could indicate a primary lung tumour or metastasis. The presence of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) further increases the risk of developing lung cancer. The reduced breath sounds in the right upper chest and wheezing may be related to the tumour\u0027s location and associated airway obstruction. In this case the neurological findings do not have a direct bearing on the pulmonary pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is a malignant tumour and refers to tumours originating in the lung parenchyma or within the bronchi. Smoking is the most common cause of lung cancer. The average age of diagnosis is 70 years old. Men are twice as likely to be diagnosed with lung cancer. The patient\u0027s age, smoking history, and symptoms of coughing up blood make lung cancer a plausible diagnosis. The presence of a mass lesion on the chest X-ray supports this possibility. Such a diagnosis might also explain this patient\u0027s weakness and muscle cramps (paraneoplastic syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThymoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a tumour that arises from the thymus gland, and it has been found to be associated with myasthenia gravis (MG) in some cases. Thymoma is one of the most common causes of MG in adults. Myasthenia gravis is an autoimmune disorder affecting the neuromuscular junction. In the given case, there is no mention of specific symptoms suggestive of myasthenia gravis, such as fluctuating muscle weakness, difficulty swallowing, or drooping eyelids (ptosis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis (TB)\u003C/strong\u003E is an infectious disease caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. It primarily affects the lungs and can cause symptoms such as cough, haemoptysis, and constitutional symptoms. While TB can be associated with haemoptysis and respiratory symptoms, other findings in the case, such as the reduced breath sounds and the mass lesion on the chest X-ray, are not typical of tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E can present with symptoms such as cough, shortness of breath, and occasionally haemoptysis. The reduced breath sounds in the right upper chest and the presence of a mass lesion on the chest X-ray could suggest pneumonia. However, additional information, such as fever or specific findings on physical examination, would be helpful to support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E, is a rare autoimmune disorder characterised by inflammation of the blood vessels, predominantly affecting the respiratory system. It can present with symptoms such as cough, hemoptysis, sinus involvement, and constitutional symptoms. While Wegener\u0027s granulomatosis could potentially explain the respiratory symptoms and hemoptysis, the reduced breath sounds and the mass lesion seen on the chest X-ray are not typically associated with this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Smoking is strongly associated with developing lung cancer."],"references":["Siddiqui F, Vaqar S, Siddiqui AH. Lung Cancer. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482357/","Siddiqui F, Vaqar S, Siddiqui AH. Lung Cancer. 2023 May 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29493979.","Thandra KC, Barsouk A, Saginala K, Aluru JS, Barsouk A. Epidemiology of lung cancer. Contemp Oncol (Pozn). 2021;25(1):45-52. doi: 10.5114/wo.2021.103829. Epub 2021 Feb 23. PMID: 33911981; PMCID: PMC8063897."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94003"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12674"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20146"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20146"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2e969310-2933-425c-839f-0323b6ece613.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2e969310-2933-425c-839f-0323b6ece613.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":540,"height":440}},{"type":"item